<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,583,608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[322,533,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Allodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboferrugineus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[322,533,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">A. alboferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[540,630,583,608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[540,630,583,608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
shows conspicuous features that greatly differ from most species in the genus: the strongly concave head with entirely dark frontoclypeus, the general coloration of the pronotum, and the transverse dark band on forewings. It superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[862,1043,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Allodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[862,1043,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">A. colombiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1052,1144,655,680]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1052,1144,655,680]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in overall coloration and pronotal shape, however, the male genitalia in 
<taxonomicName box="[672,881,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Allodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboferrugineus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[672,881,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">A. alboferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[888,978,692,717]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[888,978,692,717]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
also exhibits several unique features, for instance, the bifid process on lateral plate, spines on aedeagus, and bifid branches of aedeagal apophysis. Specimens studied that vary in pronotal coloration show a pair of yellow longitudinal bands, one next to each side of median carina, extended from base of metopidium towards the apex, merging with lateral bands on the apical third, in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[418,561,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1882,1905]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,240,1860]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1861]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Species of Dysyncritus and Allodrilus gen. nov., lateral view: 5 – 6. D. intectus Fowler, lectotype female and paralectotype male, respectively (BMNH); 7 – 9. A. nitidipennis (Funkhouser) comb. nov., (7) holotype female (USNM), (8 – 9) color and pronotal variation: female (DZUP) and male (DNA voucher MEM 136, NCSU), respectively; 10 – 12. A. alboferrugineus Evangelista sp. nov., (10) holotype female (DZUP), color variation: (11) paratype male (USNM), (12) paratype female (MZSP). Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249923/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">
Figs. 
<number box="[488,516,836,860]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" value="10.0">10</number>
–12
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[579,651,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 23 – 31" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1890,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,437,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,437,1868]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 23 – 31. Species of Dysyncritus and Allodrilus gen. nov., frontal view: 23 – 24. D. intectus Fowler, (23) lectotype female (BMNH), (24) paralectotype male (BMNH); 25. A. nitidipennis (Funkhouser) comb. nov., holotype female (USNM); 26 – 27. A. alboferrugineus Evangelista sp. nov., (26) holotype female (DZUP), color variation: (27) paratype male (MZSP); 28. A. colombiensis Evangelista sp. nov., holotype male (MPUJ); 29 – 30. A. deitzi Evangelista sp. nov., (29) holotype male (NCSU), (30) paratype female (NCSU); 31. A. granulatus Evangelista sp. nov., holotype female (USNM). Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249926/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">26–27</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[670,745,836,860]" captionStart="FIGURES 45 – 50" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1764,1787]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1743]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 45 – 50. Species of Dysyncritus and Allodrilus gen. nov., dorsal view: 45 – 46. D. intectus Fowler, (45) lectotype female (BMNH), (46) paralectotype male; 47. A. nitidipennis (Funkhouser) comb. nov, holotype female (USNM); 48 – 49. A. alboferrugineus Evangelista sp. nov., (48) holotype female (DZUP), color variation: (49) paratype male (MZSP); 50. A colombiensis Flórez-V sp. nov., holotype male (MPUJ). Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249929/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">
48– 
<number box="[715,745,836,860]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" value="49.0">49</number>
</figureCitation>
); the median carina and a thin strip of adjacent area are ferrugineous. In these specimens the pronotum seems mostly yellow, with testaceous longitudinal bands, however the male genitalia are identical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="518" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,943,968]" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet ‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[588,767,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Allodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[588,767,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">alboferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, derived from the Latin words ‘ 
<emphasis box="[1151,1211,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">albus</emphasis>
’ and ‘ 
<emphasis box="[1291,1420,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="518">ferrugineus</emphasis>
’, refers to the white and rust coloration of the pronotum.
</paragraph>
